# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chicago
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:chicago/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The **1833 Treaty of Chicago** was an agreement between the United States government and the Chippewa, Odawa, and Potawatomi tribes.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] It required them to cede to the United States government their 5,000,000 acres (2,000,000 ha) of land (including reservations) in Illinois and the Michigan Territory (which then included Wisconsin and part of Minnesota) to move west of the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In return, the tribes were given promises of various cash payments and tracts of land west of the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The treaty was one of the removal treaties to come after the passage of the Indian Removal Act.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] It was the second treaty referred to as the "Treaty of Chicago," after the 1821 Treaty of Chicago.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The negotiation of the cession treaty came roughly three years after the United States government ratified the Indian Removal Act.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In such post-Indian Removal Act cession treaties, the United States government agreed to compensate tribes for their lands, liquidate their debts, and assist them in establishing a new permanent settlement west of the Mississippi.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The Chicago Treaty of 1833 was typical of such treaties.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] One of the impetuses for the treaty were rumors that had arisen in the aftermath of the 1832 Black Hawk War that Native Americans were coming into conflict with the settlers arriving in Illinois.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The number of settlers arriving in Illinois and its surrounding area in search of farmland had increased after the 1825 opening of the Erie Canal, with the canal having opened up an easier route to travel Illinois from the Eastern United States via the Great Lakes.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Illinois residents pressured the government to remove the Indians from the land they occupied in the state, which would make that land instead available to settlers.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] One of the ways in which advocates applied pressure was by making regular reports to complain of misconduct and hostility from the Native peoples.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] These reports were relayed by John Reynolds to the United States Department of War.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The reports delivered by Reynolds and the reports made by investigators that Reynolds tasked with examining this state of affairs were founded entirely on second-hand accounts.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Officials that were closer to the situation gave accounts that contradict the reports of native misconduct and aggression.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In early 1833, the Office of Indian Affairs began exploring the prospect of removing the Potawatomi.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The latter had been previously involved in the relocation of the Potawatomi of Indiana to land west of the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In a March 5, 1833 letter, Chicago Indian Agent Owen told Herring that, after having spoken with the, "most intelligent and influential" native chiefs, he had concluded that it was very unlikely that they would agree to cede all of their lands.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] He opined that Potawatomi land cession would be expensive to secure.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] A copy of the letter was also sent to Governor Porter, who expressed the belief that the spending of great expenses would be justified if it secured the cession of the Potawatomi from their lands.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Porter also believed that the government could recoup its expense when it would sell the land to settlers.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] He also suggested that Michigan Territory could possibly secure a cession of the few remaining plots of land in the territory that were still controlled by Native Americans.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The federal government decided for there to be treaty negotiations with the Potawatomi, Odawa, Chippewa, and Kickapoo natives.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Chicago, then a town in the state of Illinois was selected as the site for a treaty to be negotiated, as it had already long established itself as a consequential trading center, was home to the Fort Dearborn garrison, and was a traditional Potawatomi resort.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On April 6, 1833, Commissioner of Indian Affairs Herring informed Chicago Indian Agent Owen that the United States Congress had approved the appropriation of $10,000 (equivalent to $346,000 in 2024) needed to hold the treaty negotiations.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Owen took charge of planning the meeting.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In preparation for the meeting, a large open arbor was built in Chicago at the corner of Rush Street and Michigan Avenue to be used as a council house during the meeting.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On April 8, 1833, Secretary of War Cass appointed the commissioners for the negotiations, naming Michigan Territory Governor Porter, Chicago Indian Agent Thomas Jefferson Vance Owen, and Colonel William Weatherford.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Weatherford, who served to represent the people of Illinois in the investigation, ultimately played a relatively negligible role in the negotiations.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Secretary Cass instructed the commissioners to work to secure the clearance of the entire region of Native American land claims.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Cass gave the commissioners warnings that he believed other treasuries for treaties had been excessively expensive, with too many individuals receiving gratuities.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Furthermore, Cass declared that no liquor should be involved in the dealings of the treaty's treasury and that its location should be on Native American territory and placed under the protection of the Army's commanding officer at Fort Dearborn.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Ewing served as secretary for the commissioners.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Plans to facilitate the travel of a Native American delegation to inspect land West of the Mississippi ahead of the negotiations were scrapped after appropriations for such an undertaking failed to come through.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Porter, who believed that would increase the difficulty of negotiating the treaty, requested in an August 23, 1833, to John F.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Schermerhorn for Schermerhorn to travel to Chicago to help with the negotiations by sharing his expert knowledge about land west of the Mississippi.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Schermerhorn would come to during the meetings, staying from September 22 through September 26, 1833.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] During the meeting, it was estimated that 3,000 out-of-town visitors descended on Chicago, including Native Americans, government officials, troops of the United States Army, land speculators, and other travelers to witness the proceedings unfold.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] At the time, Chicago was just a small village with merely 150 buildings.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Thousands of Native Americans descended on the city in the week that the meeting started.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] During the meeting, there was much unruliness among the many visitors who had flocked to the city.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The meeting was held between September 10 and October 7, 1833.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Formal proceedings of negotiations were originally scheduled to begin on September 12, 1833.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] However, the Native Americans, who were in no hurry to start the assembly, caused that to be delayed, and the first day of the council for the negotiations was held on September 14.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] At the beginning of the proceedings, a fire was kindled inside of the council house, and a peace pipe was passed between the federal government's commissioners and the chief and head men of the Native tribes.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] While the natives were against the cession of their land, it was clear from past experiences that the United States government would not take "no" for an answer once it had decided that it wanted to see Natives cede their land.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Therefore, the Natives likely saw it as in their best interests to strike a bargain, despite their desire to remain on their existing lands.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] An initial version of the treaty was agreed to on September 26, 1833.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Supplementary articles were agreed to the following day.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] After the treaty was agreed to, the commissioners gave medals to a number of Native chiefs.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] From September 30 through October 4, 1833, the commissioners examined claims that individuals held against the Natives.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] From October 5 to 6, they created a statement of their accounts and checked invoices.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Porter, who had been enthusiastic in his role in creating and finalizing the treaty, wrote a letter to Lewis Cass to report the completion of the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The treaty ceded 5,000,000 acres (2,000,000 ha) of land to the United States government.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The Potawatomi were the largest tribe in regards to population residing West of the Mississippi among the three tribes that were party to the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The sum promised to the tribes was unprecedented for such a treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The treaty marked the cession of what was the last immense tract of Native American land that remained north of the Ohio River and east of the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] That marked a landmark in accomplishing the Indian removal goals being pursued by President Andrew Jackson and the Office of Indian Affairs.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Commissioner Herring and Secretary Cass both considered the treaty to be a significant success for the United States.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In a report to the president, Secretary Cass lauded that the Natives were better off west of the Mississippi, declaring that they were, "comfortable and contented" there.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Despite the glowing endorsements of Secretary Cass and Secretary Herring, it soon became clear that the treaty would face strong opposition within the United States Senate.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] One reason was that immediately after the agreement was first reached in 1833, accusations of fraud and foul play alleging schemes of self-enrichment were made against individuals that had negotiated the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Another reason was that United States Senators felt that Native treaties were beginning to cost too much.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The primary corruption allegation was the allegation that Governor Porter had shown favor to two families with connections to him, the Kinzies and the Forsyths.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Members of those families were to profit a cumulative $100,000 (equivalent to $3,457,000 in 2024) from under terms of the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] It looked suspicious that each member of the Kinzie family earned nearly identical sums of money under the treaty's terms.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Porter's connection to the Kinzies and Forsyths was further given bad optics with the fact that John J.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Kerchavel (the latter being the husband of Maria Forsyth) had been given a virtual monopoly on furnishing goods to the treaty negotiation meetings for which they made a 50% profit.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Additional, many government officials had been hosted at the Kinzie residence during the negotiations and had well-compensated the Kinzie for the accommodations.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Porter made efforts to refute the allegations of wrongdoing.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Finding the Porter's refutations of the corruption allegations satisfactory, President Jackson submitted the treaty to the United States Senate on January 10, 1834, requesting that the Senate give its approval to the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] To address the allegations of corruption, Jackson recommended that an individual agent be sent to go to Chicago and investigate the claims there.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The Senate referred the treaty to the Senate Committee on Indian Affairs.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] After giving due consideration to objections to the treaty, the committee decided that there was not a need for it to fight the treaty's ratification.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On April 2, 1834, the committee submitted its report and recommendations to the full Senate.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On October 1, 1834, alterations to the treaty were proposed.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On February 21, 1835, the Senate gave its consent to the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The treaty was ratified that same day by the signature of President Jackson.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The treaty's statute reference is 7 Stat., 431.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On March 3, 1835, federal appropriations for the treaty were approved.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] The appropriations saw $1,032,689.53 (equivalent to $33,057,000 in 2024) allocated for grants provided by the treaty.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In accordance with the treaty and the federal government's goals, the United States government acted to carry out the removal of members of the party Native American tribes out of the lands east of the Mississippi.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] As the treaty was ratified in 1835, it would be by 1838 that the Natives had to leave.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] On August 31, 1835, before the residents of Chicago, in an act of defiance ahead of their impending removal, five-hundred Native American warriors gathered in Chicago in full dress and brandishing tomahawks and put on dramatic war dance displays.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] That was the last recorded war dance in the Chicago area.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] A plaque in suburban Western Springs, Illinois, near its border with Indian Head Park at Plainfield and Wolf Roads, marks the location of an 1835 camp site for some of the final Native Americans to depart the Chicago area.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] Some natives moved to northern Wisconsin, rather than moving west of the Mississippi.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] For years, only the Potawatomi that had moved west of the Mississippi to Kansas would receive the stipulated annuities from the United States government.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] However, the United States government moved to rectify that in 1913, when it paid the Wisconsin Potawatomi $447,339 (equivalent to $10,414,000 in 2024).
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] In 1838, the remaining Potawatomi in the Chicago region were forcibly removed from their village (which was burned) and marched over 660 miles at gunpoint from Indiana to Kansas.
[src:chicago/1833-treaty-of-chicago] This event is referred to as the "Trail of Death".
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chicago/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:chicago/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The **1860 Republican National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met May 16–18 in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] It was held to nominate the Republican Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1860 election.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The convention selected former representative Abraham Lincoln of Illinois for president and Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine for vice president.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Entering the 1860 convention, Senator William H.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward of New York was generally regarded as the front-runner, but Lincoln, Governor Salmon P.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase of Ohio, former representative Edward Bates of Missouri, and Senator Simon Cameron of Pennsylvania all commanded support from a significant share of delegates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward led on the first ballot but fell short of a majority, while Lincoln finished in a strong second place.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Cameron's delegates shifted to Lincoln on the second ballot, leaving Lincoln essentially tied with Seward.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln clinched the nomination on the third ballot after consolidating support from more delegates who had backed candidates other than Seward.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Hamlin was nominated on the second vice presidential ballot, defeating Cassius Clay of Kentucky and several other candidates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The ticket of Lincoln and Hamlin went on to win the 1860 general election.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] After taking office in 1861, Lincoln appointed all four of his major opponents to his cabinet: Seward for secretary of state, Chase for secretary of the treasury (and later for chief justice), Bates for attorney general, and Cameron for secretary of war.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] By 1860 the dissolution of the Whig Party in America had become an accomplished fact, with establishment Whig politicians, former Free Soilers, and a certain number of anti-Catholic populists from the Know Nothing movement flocking to the banner of the fledgling anti-slavery Republican Party.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] While 1856 Republican presidential nominee John C.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Frémont had met with failure, party gains were made throughout the Northern United States as the sectional crisis over slavery intensified.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Morgan were interested in holding the 1860 convention in a border state.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Party leaders sought to hold their 1860 nominating convention in the burgeoning Middle Western trade center of Chicago, then a city of some 110,000 people.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The city had no sufficiently large meeting hall, so an appropriation was made for a temporary wood-frame assembly hall – known as the "Wigwam" – to seat ten thousand delegates, guests, and observers.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The rapidly designed and constructed building proved well fit for the purpose, featuring excellent lines of sight and stellar acoustics, allowing even an ordinary speaker to be heard throughout the room.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The Convention commanded the interest and attention of a multitude of curious citizens who crowded the "Wigwam" to the rafters.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Delegations were seated by state and the gathering was virtually devoid of Southern participation, with no delegations attending from the slave states of North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, Arkansas, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, and Florida.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Some 86 votes were apportioned to the six states of New England.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Slave and border states with substantial delegations under the rules (but with small actual party organizations) included Kentucky (23), Virginia (23), and Missouri (18).
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The total of all credentialed delegate votes was 466.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] With the convention called to order on May 16, former U.S.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Representative David Wilmot of Pennsylvania was elected temporary chairman of the gathering.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He had been the author in 1848 of the Wilmot Proviso which would have banned slavery from new states incorporated into the Union.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Organizational tasks filled the rest of the first day's activities, including the appointment of a Credentials Committee and a Resolutions Committee.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] There were no contested seats although a delegation purporting to represent the state of Texas was ruled ineligible by the Credentials Committee.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] A Platform Committee was also named, including one delegate from every state and territory in attendance.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] This committee began its work at once and completed its task with a report on the evening of the second day, May 17.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The platform was drawn up by the Platform Committee chaired by Judge William Jessup of Pennsylvania.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The reading of the platform was received with stormy applause and an immediate move followed to adopt the document unanimously and without amendments.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The matter was hastily reconsidered by the convention, and with the addition of the amendment the disgruntled Mr.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Giddings returned to his seat, crisis resolved.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The 1860 Republican platform consisted of 17 declarations of principle, of which 10 dealt directly with the issues of "free soil", slavery, the Fugitive Slave Act, and the preservation of the Union, while the remaining 7 dealt with other issues.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Clauses 12 through 16 of the platform called for a protective tariff, enactment of the Homestead Act, maintaining the current naturalization laws and full rights to all "native or naturalized" citizens, internal improvements, and the construction of a Pacific railroad.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] In addition to the preservation of the Union, all five of these additional promises were enacted by the Thirty-seventh Congress and implemented by Abraham Lincoln or the presidents who immediately succeeded him.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The Republican National Convention met in mid-May 1860, after the Democrats had been forced to adjourn their convention in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] With the Democrats in disarray and a sweep of the Northern states possible, the Republicans felt confident going into their convention in Chicago.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward from New York was considered the front-runner, followed Salmon P.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase from Ohio, and Missouri's Edward Bates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Abraham Lincoln from Illinois, was lesser known, and was not considered to have a good chance against Seward.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward had been governor and senator of New York, was from firm Whig backgrounds, and was a very able politician.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Clay, and Benjamin Wade, who might be able to win if the convention deadlocked.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] As the convention developed, however, it was revealed that frontrunners Seward, Chase, and Bates had each alienated factions of the Republican Party.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Seward had been painted as a radical, and his speeches on slavery predicted inevitable conflict, which spooked moderate delegates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He also was firmly opposed to nativism, which further weakened his position.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He had also been abandoned by his longtime friend and political ally Horace Greeley, publisher of the influential *New-York Tribune*.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Chase, a former Democrat, had alienated many of the former Whigs by his coalition with the Democrats in the late 1840s.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He had also opposed tariffs demanded by Pennsylvania, and even had opposition from his own delegation from Ohio.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] However, Chase's firm antislavery stance made him popular with the radical Republicans.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] But what he had in policy he lacked in charisma and political acumen.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Bates' candidacy was pushed by Francis Preston Blair and Francis Preston Blair Jr. despite Bates not being a member of the party.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] They had the Republican parties of Missouri and Maryland send delegations pledged to Bates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Greeley and Schuyler Colfax were interested in his candidacy, but he failed to receive a large amount of support from northern or border state delegates.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The conservative Bates was an unlikely candidate.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln was not unknown; he had gained prominence in the Lincoln–Douglas debates, and had served as a member of the U.S.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He had been quietly eyeing a run since the Lincoln–Douglas debates in 1858, ensuring that the debates were widely published, and that a biography of himself was published.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He gained great notability with his February 1860 Cooper Union speech, which may have ensured him the nomination.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] At that time he had not yet announced his intentions to run, but it was a superb speech.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Delivered in Seward's home state, and attended by Greeley, Lincoln used the speech to show that the Republican party was a party of moderates, not crazed fanatics as the South and Democrats claimed.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Afterwards, Lincoln was in much demand for speaking engagements.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] As the convention approached, Lincoln did not campaign very actively, as the "office was expected to seek the man".
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] So it did at the Illinois state convention in downstate Decatur, a week before the national convention.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Young politician Richard Oglesby had secretly found several fence rails from the Hanks-Lincoln farm that Lincoln may have split as a youngster, and paraded them into the convention with a banner that proclaimed Lincoln to be "The Rail Candidate" for president.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln received a thunderous ovation, surpassing the expectations of him and his political allies.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Even with such support from his home state, Lincoln faced a difficult task if he was to win the nomination.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He set about ensuring that he was the second choice of most delegates, realizing that the first round of voting at the convention was unlikely to produce a clear winner.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He engineered that the convention would happen in Chicago, which would be inherently friendly to the Illinois-based Lincoln.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] He also made sure that the Illinois delegation would vote as a bloc for him.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln did not attend the convention in person, and left the task of delegate wrangling to his friends Leonard Swett, Ward Hill Lamon, and David Davis.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln's team even printed counterfeit convention tickets, which they handed out to his supporters.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] During the night of May 17–18, they worked frantically to win anti-Seward delegates for Lincoln.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] They showed that Lincoln already had the most support after Seward, which persuaded some.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] They also made a deal with Simon Cameron of Pennsylvania, who recognized that he had no chance of winning the nomination himself.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Cameron controlled the Pennsylvania delegation, and he offered to trade his support for the promise of a cabinet position for himself and control of Federal patronage in Pennsylvania.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln did not want to make any such deal; from Springfield, he telegraphed to Davis "I authorize no bargains and will be bound by none".
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Despite this restriction, Davis reached an understanding with Cameron, which eventually led to Cameron's appointment as Secretary of War.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] The next day (May 18), when voting for the nomination began, Seward led on the first ballot with Lincoln a distant second.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] But on the second ballot, the Pennsylvania delegation switched to Lincoln, as well as some other delegates, putting him in a near-tie with Seward.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Lincoln's combination of a moderate stance on slavery, long support for economic issues, his western origins, and strong oratory proved to be exactly what the delegates wanted in a president.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] On the third ballot on May 18, Lincoln secured the nomination overwhelmingly.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Senator Hannibal Hamlin from Maine was nominated for vice-president, defeating Cassius M.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Among other accounts, an article, entitled "The Four Votes", published in the May 19, 1860, edition of the *Chicago Press and Tribune* attests that after seeing how close Lincoln was to the 234 votes needed, Robert K.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Enos, a member of the Ohio delegation, was responsible for getting three fellow Ohio delegates to announce after the close of the third ballot that they were shifting their four votes to Lincoln, giving him sufficient votes to win the nomination.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] This triggered an avalanche towards Lincoln on the fourth ballot, with a final count of 350 votes for Lincoln out of 466 cast.
[src:chicago/1860-republican-national-convention] Senator Hannibal Hamlin of Maine was nominated for vice president, defeating Cassius M.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:chicago/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:chicago/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago was incorporated as a city in 1837 near a portage between the Great Lakes and the Mississippi River watershed.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It grew rapidly in the mid-19th century.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed several square miles and left more than 100,000 homeless, but Chicago's population continued to grow.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago made noted contributions to urban planning and architecture, such as the Chicago School, the development of the City Beautiful movement, and the steel-framed skyscraper.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is an international hub for finance, culture, commerce, industry, education, technology, telecommunications, and transportation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It has the largest and most diverse finance derivatives market in the world, generating 20% of all volume in commodities and financial futures alone.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] O'Hare International Airport is routinely ranked among the world's top ten busiest airports by passenger traffic, and the region is also the nation's railroad hub.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Chicago area has one of the highest gross domestic products (GDP) of any urban region in the world, ranking sixth globally, generating over $919 billion in 2024.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's economy is diverse, with no single industry employing more than 14% of the workforce.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is a major destination for tourism, with nearly 57 million people visiting its cultural institutions, Lake Michigan beaches, restaurants, and other tourist sites in 2025.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's culture has made significant contributions to the visual arts, literature, film, theater, comedy (especially improvisational comedy), food, dance, and music (particularly jazz, blues, soul, hip-hop, gospel, industrial, and electronic dance music, especially house music).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is home to the Chicago Symphony Orchestra and the Lyric Opera of Chicago, while the Art Institute of Chicago has an influential visual arts museum and art school.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Chicago area is home to the University of Chicago, Northwestern University, and the University of Illinois Chicago, among other institutions of higher education.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It also hosts the Barack Obama Presidential Center.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Professional sports in Chicago include all major professional leagues, including two Major League Baseball teams.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city also hosts the Chicago Marathon, one of the World Marathon Majors.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The name *Chicago* is derived from a French rendering of the indigenous Miami–Illinois word *šikaakwa*, which was a name for a wild relative of onion and garlic known to modern botanists as *Allium tricoccum*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The first known reference to the site of the city of Chicago as "*Checagou*" was by Robert de La Salle around 1679 in a memoir.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Henri Joutel, in his journal of 1688, noted that the eponymous wild "garlic" grew profusely in the area.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city has had several nicknames throughout its history, such as the Windy City, Chi-Town, Second City, and City of the Big Shoulders.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the mid-18th century, the area was inhabited by the Potawatomi, an indigenous tribe who had succeeded the Miami, Sauk and Meskwaki peoples in this region.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The first known permanent settler in Chicago was a trader, Jean Baptiste Point du Sable.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Du Sable was of African descent, perhaps born in the French colony of Saint-Domingue (Haiti), and he established the settlement in the 1780s.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] He is commonly known as the "Founder of Chicago".
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1795, following the victory of the new United States in the Northwest Indian War, an area that was to be part of Chicago was turned over to the U.S. for a military post by native tribes in accordance with the Treaty of Greenville.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Army constructed Fort Dearborn, which was destroyed during the War of 1812 in the Battle of Fort Dearborn by the Potawatomi before being later rebuilt.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] After the War of 1812, the Odawa, Ojibwe, and Potawatomi tribes ceded additional land to the United States in the 1816 Treaty of St.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Potawatomi were forcibly removed from their land after the 1833 Treaty of Chicago and sent west of the Mississippi River as part of the federal policy of Indian removal.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On August 12, 1833, the Town of Chicago was organized with a population of about 200.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Within seven years it grew to more than 6,000 people.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On June 15, 1835, the first public land sales began with Edmund Dick Taylor as Receiver of Public Monies.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The City of Chicago was incorporated on Saturday, March 4, 1837, and for several decades was the world's fastest-growing city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] As the site of the Chicago Portage, the city became an important transportation hub between the eastern and western United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's first railway, Galena and Chicago Union Railroad, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal opened in 1848.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The canal allowed steamboats and sailing ships on the Great Lakes to connect to the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A flourishing economy brought residents from rural communities and immigrants from abroad.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Manufacturing and retail and finance sectors became dominant, influencing the American economy.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Chicago Board of Trade (established 1848) listed the first-ever standardized "exchange-traded" forward contracts, which were called futures contracts.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the 1850s, Chicago gained national political prominence as the home of Senator Stephen Douglas, the champion of the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the "popular sovereignty" approach to the issue of the spread of slavery.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] These issues also helped propel another Illinoisan, Abraham Lincoln, to the national stage.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Lincoln was nominated in Chicago for U.S. president at the 1860 Republican National Convention, which was held in a purpose-built auditorium called the Wigwam.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] He defeated Douglas in the general election, and this set the stage for the American Civil War.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] To accommodate rapid population growth and demand for better sanitation, the city improved its infrastructure.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In February 1856, Chicago's Common Council approved Chesbrough's plan to build the United States' first comprehensive sewerage system.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The project raised much of central Chicago to a new grade with the use of jackscrews for raising buildings.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] While elevating Chicago, and at first improving the city's health, the untreated sewage and industrial waste now flowed into the Chicago River, and subsequently into Lake Michigan, polluting the city's primary freshwater source.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city responded by tunneling two miles (3.2 km) out into Lake Michigan to newly built water cribs.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1900, the problem of sewage contamination was largely resolved when the city completed a major engineering feat.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It reversed the flow of the Chicago River so that the water flowed away from Lake Michigan rather than into it.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This project began with the construction and improvement of the Illinois and Michigan Canal, and was completed with the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal that connects to the Illinois River, which flows into the Mississippi River.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On October 8, 1871, the Great Chicago Fire destroyed an area about 4 miles (6.4 km) long and 1-mile (1.6 km) wide, a large section of the city at the time.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] At least 300 people were killed and over 100,000 were left homeless from the fire.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] However, much of the city, including railroads and stockyards, survived intact, and from the ruins of the previous wooden structures arose more modern constructions of steel and stone.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] These set a precedent for worldwide construction.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] During its rebuilding period, Chicago constructed the world's first skyscraper in 1885, using steel-skeleton construction.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Labor conflicts followed the industrial boom and the rapid expansion of the labor pool during the Gilded Age, including the Haymarket affair on May 4, 1886, and in 1894 the Pullman Strike.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Anarchist and socialist groups played prominent roles in creating very large and highly organized labor actions.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Concern for social problems among Chicago's immigrant poor led Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr to found Hull House in 1889.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Programs that were developed there became a model for the new field of social work.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] During the 1870s and 1880s, Chicago attained national stature as the leader in the movement to improve public health.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] City laws and later, state laws that upgraded standards for the medical profession and fought urban epidemics of cholera, smallpox, and yellow fever were both passed and enforced.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] These laws became templates for public health reform in other cities and states.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city established many large, well-landscaped municipal parks, which also included public sanitation facilities.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The chief advocate for improving public health in Chicago was John H.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Rauch established a plan for Chicago's park system in 1866.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] He created Lincoln Park by closing a cemetery filled with shallow graves, and in 1867, in response to an outbreak of cholera he helped establish a new Chicago Board of Health.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Ten years later, he became the secretary and then the president of the first Illinois State Board of Health, which carried out most of its activities in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the 1800s, Chicago became the nation's railroad hub, and by 1910 over 20 railroads operated passenger service out of six different downtown terminals.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1883, Chicago's railway managers needed a general time convention, so they developed the standardized system of North American time zones.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This system for telling time spread throughout the continent.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The desire to join the city was driven by municipal services that the city could provide its residents.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1893, Chicago hosted the World's Columbian Exposition on former marshland at the present location of Jackson Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Exposition drew 27.5 million visitors, and is considered the most influential world's fair in history.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city's municipal device, a Y within a circle, was the result of a contest run by the *Chicago Tribune* in 1892, in anticipation of the Columbian Exposition.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The University of Chicago, formerly at another location, moved to the same South Side location in 1892.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The term "midway" for a fair or carnival referred originally to the Midway Plaisance, a strip of park land that still runs through the University of Chicago campus and connects the Washington and Jackson Parks.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's flourishing economy attracted huge numbers of new immigrants from Europe and migrants from the Eastern United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Of the total population in 1900, more than 77% were either foreign-born or born in the United States of foreign parentage.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Germans, Irish, Poles, Swedes, and Czechs made up nearly two-thirds of the foreign-born population (by 1900, whites were 98.1% of the city's population).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] During World War I and the 1920s there was a major expansion in industry.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The availability of jobs attracted African Americans from the Southern United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Between 1910 and 1930, the African American population of Chicago increased dramatically, from 44,103 to 233,903.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This Great Migration had an immense cultural impact, called the Chicago Black Renaissance, part of the New Negro Movement, in art, literature, and music.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Continuing racial tensions and violence in the city, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919, also occurred.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The ratification of the 18th amendment to the Constitution in 1919 made the production and sale (including exportation) of alcoholic beverages illegal in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This ushered in the beginning of what is known as the gangster era, a time that roughly spans from 1919 until 1933 when Prohibition was repealed.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The 1920s saw gangsters, including Al Capone, Dion O'Banion, Bugs Moran and Tony Accardo battle law enforcement and each other on the streets of Chicago during the Prohibition era.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago was the location of the infamous St.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Valentine's Day Massacre in 1929, when Al Capone sent men to gun down members of a rival gang, North Side, led by Bugs Moran, leaving seven rival members dead.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] From 1920 to 1921, the city was affected by a series of tenant rent strikes, which led to the formation of the Chicago Tenants Protective association, passage of the Kessenger tenant laws, and of a heat ordinance that legally required flats to be kept above 68 °F during winter months by landlords.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago was the first American city to have a homosexual-rights organization.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The organization, formed in 1924, was called the Society for Human Rights.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It produced the first American publication for homosexuals, *Friendship and Freedom*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Police and political pressure caused the organization to disband.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Great Depression brought unprecedented suffering to Chicago, in no small part due to the city's heavy reliance on heavy industry.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Notably, industrial areas on the south side and neighborhoods lining both branches of the Chicago River were devastated; by 1933 over 50% of industrial jobs in the city had been lost, and unemployment rates amongst blacks and Latinos in the city were over 40%.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Republican political machine in Chicago was utterly destroyed by the economic crisis, and every mayor since 1931 has been a Democrat.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] From 1928 to 1933, the city witnessed a tax revolt, and the city was unable to meet payroll or provide relief efforts.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The fiscal crisis was resolved by 1933, and at the same time, federal relief funding began to flow into Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago was also a hotbed of labor activism, with Unemployed Councils contributing heavily in the early depression to create solidarity for the poor and demand relief; these organizations were created by socialist and communist groups.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By 1935, the Workers Alliance of America began organizing the poor, workers, the unemployed.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the spring of 1937 Republic Steel Works witnessed the Memorial Day massacre of 1937 in the neighborhood of East Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1933, Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak was fatally wounded in Miami, Florida, during a failed assassination attempt on President-elect Franklin D.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1933 and 1934, the city celebrated its centennial by hosting the Century of Progress International Exposition World's Fair.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The theme of the fair was technological innovation over the century since Chicago's founding.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] During World War II, the city of Chicago alone produced more steel than the United Kingdom every year from 1939 – 1945, and more than Nazi Germany from 1943 – 1945.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Great Migration, which had been on pause due to the Depression, resumed at an even faster pace in the second wave, as hundreds of thousands of blacks from the South arrived in the city to work in the steel mills, railroads, and shipping yards.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On December 2, 1942, physicist Enrico Fermi conducted the world's first controlled nuclear reaction at the University of Chicago as part of the top-secret Manhattan Project.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This led to the creation of the atomic bomb by the United States, which it used in World War II in 1945.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Daley, a Democrat, was elected in 1955, in the era of machine politics.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1956, the city conducted its last major expansion when it annexed the land under O'Hare airport, including a small portion of DuPage County.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By the 1960s, white residents in several neighborhoods left the city for the suburban areas – in many American cities, a process known as white flight – as Blacks continued to move beyond the Black Belt.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] While home loan discriminatory redlining against blacks continued, the real estate industry practiced what became known as blockbusting, completely changing the racial composition of whole neighborhoods.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Structural changes in industry, such as globalization and job outsourcing, caused heavy job losses for lower-skilled workers.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] At its peak during the 1960s, some 250,000 workers were employed in the steel industry in Chicago, but the steel crisis of the 1970s and 1980s reduced this number to just 28,000 in 2015.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1966, Martin Luther King Jr. and Albert Raby led the Chicago Freedom Movement, which culminated in agreements between Mayor Richard J.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Two years later, the city hosted the tumultuous 1968 Democratic National Convention, which featured physical confrontations both inside and outside the convention hall, with anti-war protesters, journalists and bystanders being beaten by police.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Major construction projects, including the Sears Tower (now known as the Willis Tower, which in 1974 became the world's tallest building), University of Illinois at Chicago, McCormick Place, and O'Hare International Airport, were undertaken during Richard J.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1979, Jane Byrne, the city's first female mayor, was elected.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] She was notable for temporarily moving into the crime-ridden Cabrini-Green housing project and leading Chicago's school system out of a financial crisis.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1983, Harold Washington became the first black mayor of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Washington's first term in office directed attention to poor and previously neglected minority neighborhoods.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] He was re‑elected in 1987 but died of a heart attack soon after.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Washington was succeeded by 6th ward alderperson Eugene Sawyer, who was elected by the Chicago City Council and served until a special election.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] His accomplishments included improvements to parks and creating incentives for sustainable development, as well as closing Meigs Field in the middle of the night and destroying the runways.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] After successfully running for re-election five times, and becoming Chicago's longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Daley declined to run for a seventh term.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1992, a construction accident near the Kinzie Street Bridge produced a breach connecting the Chicago River to a tunnel below, which was part of an abandoned freight tunnel system extending throughout the downtown Loop district.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The tunnels filled with 250 million US gallons (1,000,000 m3) of water, affecting buildings throughout the district and forcing a shutdown of electrical power.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The area was shut down for three days and some buildings did not reopen for weeks; losses were estimated at $1.95 billion.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On February 23, 2011, Rahm Emanuel, a former White House Chief of Staff and member of the House of Representatives, won the mayoral election.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Emanuel was sworn in as mayor on May 16, 2011, and won re-election in 2015.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Lori Lightfoot, the city's first African American woman mayor and its first openly LGBTQ mayor, was elected to succeed Emanuel as mayor in 2019.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] All three city-wide elective offices were held by women (and women of color) for the first time in Chicago history: in addition to Lightfoot, the city clerk was Anna Valencia and the city treasurer was Melissa Conyears-Ervin.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] On May 15, 2023, Brandon Johnson assumed office as the 57th mayor of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is located in northeastern Illinois on the southwestern shores of freshwater Lake Michigan.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It is the principal city in the Chicago Metropolitan Area, situated in both the Midwestern United States and the Great Lakes region.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city rests on a continental divide at the site of the Chicago Portage, connecting the Mississippi River and the Great Lakes watersheds.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In addition to it lying beside Lake Michigan, two rivers—the Chicago River in downtown and the Calumet River in the industrial far South Side—flow either entirely or partially through the city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's history and economy are closely tied to its proximity to Lake Michigan.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] While the Chicago River historically handled much of the region's waterborne cargo, today's huge lake freighters use the city's Lake Calumet Harbor on the South Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The lake also provides another positive effect: moderating Chicago's climate, making waterfront neighborhoods slightly warmer in winter and cooler in summer.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] When Chicago was founded in 1837, most of the early building was around the mouth of the Chicago River, as can be seen on a map of the city's original 58 blocks.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The overall grade of the city's central, built-up areas is relatively consistent with the natural flatness of its overall natural geography, generally exhibiting only slight differentiation otherwise.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The average land elevation is 579 ft (176.5 m) above sea level.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] While measurements vary somewhat, the lowest points are along the lake shore at 578 ft (176.2 m), while the highest point, at 672 ft (205 m), is the morainal ridge of Blue Island in the city's far south side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Lake Shore Drive runs adjacent to a large portion of Chicago's waterfront.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Some of the parks along the waterfront include Lincoln Park, Grant Park, Burnham Park, and Jackson Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] There are 24 public beaches across 26 miles (42 km) of the waterfront.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Landfill extends into portions of the lake providing space for Navy Pier, Northerly Island, the Museum Campus, and large portions of the McCormick Place Convention Center.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Most of the city's high-rise commercial and residential buildings are close to the waterfront.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] An informal name for the entire Chicago metropolitan area is "Chicagoland", which generally means the city and all its suburbs, though different organizations have slightly different definitions.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Major sections of the city include the central business district, called the Loop, and the North, South, and West Sides.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The three sides of the city are represented on the Flag of Chicago by three horizontal white stripes.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The North Side is the city's most densely populated residential section, and many high-rises are on this side of the city along the lakefront.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The South Side is the city's largest section, encompassing roughly 60% of its land area.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The South Side contains most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the late 1920s, sociologists at the University of Chicago subdivided the city into 75 distinct community areas, plus O'Hare in 1956 and Edgewater in 1980 for a total of 77.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The community areas can further be subdivided into over 200 informally defined neighborhoods.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's streets were laid out in a street grid that grew from the city's original townsite plot, which was bounded by Lake Michigan on the east, North Avenue on the north, Wood Street on the west, and 22nd Street on the south.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Streets following the Public Land Survey System section lines later became arterial streets in outlying sections.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] As new additions to the city were platted, city ordinance required them to be laid out with eight streets to the mile in one direction and sixteen in the other direction, about one street per 200 meters in one direction and one street per 100 meters in the other direction.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The grid's regularity provided an efficient means of developing new real estate property.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A scattering of diagonal streets, many of them originally Native American trails, also cross the city (Elston, Milwaukee, Ogden, Lincoln, etc.).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Many additional diagonal streets were recommended in the Plan of Chicago, but only the extension of Ogden Avenue was ever constructed.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 2021, Chicago was ranked the fourth-most walkable large city in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Many of the city's residential streets have a wide patch of grass or trees between the street and the sidewalk itself.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] This helps to keep pedestrians on the sidewalk further away from the street traffic.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's Western Avenue is the longest continuous urban street in the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Other notable streets include Michigan Avenue, State Street, 95th Street, Cicero Avenue, Clark Street, and Belmont Avenue.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The City Beautiful movement inspired Chicago's boulevards and parkways.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The destruction caused by the Great Chicago Fire led to the largest building boom in the history of the nation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1885, the first steel-framed high-rise building, the Home Insurance Building, rose in the city as Chicago ushered in the skyscraper era, which would then be followed by many other cities around the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Today, Chicago's skyline is among the world's tallest and densest.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Some of the United States' tallest towers are located in Chicago; Willis Tower (formerly Sears Tower) is the third tallest building in the Western Hemisphere after One World Trade Center, and Central Park Tower.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Loop's historic buildings include the Chicago Board of Trade Building, the Fine Arts Building, 35 East Wacker, and the Chicago Building, 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments by Mies van der Rohe.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Many other architects have left their impression on the Chicago skyline such as Daniel Burnham, Louis Sullivan, Charles B.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Merchandise Mart, once the largest building in the world, had its own zip code until 2008, and stands near the junction of the North and South branches of the Chicago River.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Presently, the four tallest buildings in the city are Willis Tower (formerly the Sears Tower, also a building with its own zip code), Trump International Hotel and Tower, the Aon Center (previously the Standard Oil Building), and the John Hancock Center.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Industrial districts, such as some areas on the South Side, the areas along the Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal, and the Northwest Indiana area are clustered.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago gave its name to the Chicago School and was home to the Prairie School, two movements in architecture.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Multiple kinds and scales of houses, townhouses, condominiums, and apartment buildings can be found throughout Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Large swaths of the city's residential areas away from the lake are characterized by brick bungalows built from the early 20th century through the end of World War II.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is also a prominent center of the Polish Cathedral style of church architecture.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Chicago suburb of Oak Park was home to famous architect Frank Lloyd Wright, who had designed The Robie House located near the University of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A popular tourist activity is to take an architecture boat tour along the Chicago River.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is famous for its outdoor public art with donors establishing funding for such art as far back as Benjamin Ferguson's 1905 trust.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A number of Chicago's public art works are by modern figurative artists.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Some events which shaped the city's history have also been memorialized by art works, including the Great Northern Migration (Saar) and the centennial of statehood for Illinois.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Finally, two fountains near the Loop also function as monumental works of art: Plensa's Crown Fountain as well as Burnham and Bennett's Buckingham Fountain.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city mostly lies within the typical hot-summer humid continental climate (Köppen: *Dfa*), and experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with frequent heat waves.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The July daily average temperature is 75.4 °F (24.1 °C), with afternoon temperatures peaking at 84.5 °F (29.2 °C).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In a normal summer, temperatures reach at least 90 °F (32 °C) on 17 days, with lakefront locations staying cooler when winds blow off the lake.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Blizzards do occur, such as in winter 2011.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The normal winter high from December through March is about 36 °F (2 °C).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] January and February are the coldest months.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A polar vortex in January 2019 nearly broke the city's cold record of −27 °F (−33 °C), which was set on January 20, 1985.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Measurable snowfall can continue through the first or second week of April.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, short seasons, typically with low humidity.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Dew point temperatures in the summer range from an average of 55.8 °F (13.2 °C) in June to 61.7 °F (16.5 °C) in July.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] They can reach nearly 80 °F (27 °C), such as during the July 2019 heat wave.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The city lies within USDA plant hardiness zone 6a, transitioning to 5b in the suburbs.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] According to the National Weather Service, Chicago's highest official temperature reading of 105 °F (41 °C) was recorded on July 24, 1934.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Midway Airport reached 109 °F (43 °C) one day prior and recorded a heat index of 125 °F (52 °C) during the 1995 heatwave.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The lowest official temperature of −27 °F (−33 °C) was recorded on January 20, 1985, at O'Hare Airport.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Most of the city's rainfall is brought by thunderstorms, averaging 38 a year.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The region is prone to severe thunderstorms during the spring and summer which can produce large hail, damaging winds, and occasionally tornadoes.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Notably, the F4 Oak Lawn tornado moved through the South Side of the city on April 21, 1967, moving onto Lake Michigan as a waterspout.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Downtown Chicago was struck by an F3 tornado on May 6, 1876, again moving out over Lake Michigan.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Like other major cities, Chicago experiences an urban heat island, making the city and its suburbs milder than surrounding rural areas, especially at night and in winter.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Northeast winds from wintertime cyclones departing south of the region sometimes bring the city lake-effect snow.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] During its first hundred years, Chicago was one of the fastest-growing cities in the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] When founded in 1833, fewer than 200 people had settled on what was then the American frontier.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By the time of its first census, seven years later, the population had reached over 4,000.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the forty years from 1850 to 1890, the city's population grew from slightly under 30,000 to over 1 million.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By the 1890 census, Chicago was the second most populous city in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By 1900, it was the fifth largest in the world behind Berlin, Paris, New York, and London, and the largest city founded in the prior century.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Within sixty years of the Great Chicago Fire of 1871, the population went from about 300,000 to over 3 million, and reached its highest ever recorded population of 3.6 million for the 1950 census.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] To these ethnic groups, the basis of the city's industrial working class, were added an additional influx of African Americans from the American South as part of the Great Migration—with Chicago's black population doubling between 1910 and 1920 and doubling again between 1920 and 1930.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago has a significant Bosnian population, many of whom arrived in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, the great majority of African Americans moving to Chicago settled in a so‑called "Black Belt" on the city's South Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A large number of blacks also settled on the West Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By 1930, two-thirds of Chicago's black population lived in sections of the city which were 90% black in racial composition.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Around that time, the block of 4600 Winthrop Avenue in the Uptown neighborhood was the only one in the neighborhood on which African Americans could live or open establishments.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's South Side emerged as United States second-largest urban black concentration, following New York's Harlem.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 1990, Chicago's South Side and the adjoining south suburbs constituted the largest black majority region in the entire United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Since the 1980s, Chicago has had a massive exodus of African Americans (primarily from the South and West sides) to its suburbs or outside its metropolitan area.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The above average crime and cost of living were leading reasons for the fast declining African American population in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Most of Chicago's foreign-born population were born in Mexico, Poland or India.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] A 2020 study estimated the total Jewish population of the Chicago metropolitan area, both religious and irreligious, at 319,500.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago's population declined in the latter half of the 20th century, from over 3.6 million in 1950 down to under 2.7 million by 2010.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] By the time of the official census count in 1990, it was overtaken by Los Angeles as the United States' second largest city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] It then saw a rise in population for the 2000 census, a decrease in 2010, and another increase for the 2020 census.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] According to U.S. census estimates as of July 2019, Chicago's largest racial or ethnic group is non-Hispanic White at 32.8% of the population, Blacks at 30.1% and the Hispanic population at 29.0% of the population.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago became a "de jure" sanctuary city in 2012 when Mayor Rahm Emanuel and the City Council passed the Welcoming City Ordinance.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Census Bureau's American Community Survey data estimates for 2022, the median income for a household in the city was $70,386, and the per capita income was $45,449.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Male full-time workers had a median income of $68,870 versus $60,987 for females.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] About 17.2% of the population lived below the poverty line.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 2018, Chicago ranked seventh globally for the highest number of ultra-high-net-worth residents with roughly 3,300 residents worth more than $30 million.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Persons who did not report or classify an ancestry were 548,790.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago has the third-largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, and queer (LGBTQ) population in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Since the 2013 legalization of same-sex marriage in Illinois, over 10,000 same-sex couples have wed in Illinois' Cook County, a majority of them in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is the first U.S. city to have a pro-gay organization and consistently ranks as one of the most LGBTQ-friendly cities in the nation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Lake View and Edgewater are historically the epicenters of LGBTQ culture in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] According to a 2014 study by the Pew Research Center, Christianity is the most prevalently practiced religion in Chicago (71%), with the city being the fourth-most religious metropolis in the United States after Dallas, Atlanta and Houston.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Roman Catholicism and Protestantism are the largest branches (34% and 35% respectively), followed by Eastern Orthodoxy and Jehovah's Witnesses with 1% each.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago also has a sizable non-Christian population.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Non-Christian groups include Irreligious (22%), Judaism (3%), Islam (2%), Buddhism (1%) and Hinduism (1%).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Chicago is the headquarters of several religious denominations, including the Evangelical Covenant Church and the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The Fourth Presbyterian Church is one of the largest Presbyterian congregations in the United States based on memberships.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Since the 20th century Chicago has also been the headquarters of the Assyrian Church of the East.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] In 2014 the Catholic Church was the largest individual Christian denomination (34%), with the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago being the largest Catholic jurisdiction.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Evangelical Protestantism form the largest theological Protestant branch (16%), followed by Mainline Protestants (11%), and historically Black churches (8%).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Among denominational Protestant branches, Baptists formed the largest group in Chicago (10%); followed by Nondenominational (5%); Lutherans (4%); and Pentecostals (3%).
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Non-Christian faiths accounted for 7% of the religious population in 2014.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Judaism has at least 261,000 adherents which is 3% of the population.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] The first two Parliament of the World's Religions in 1893 and 1993 were held in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Many international religious leaders have visited Chicago, including Mother Teresa, the Dalai Lama and Pope John Paul II in 1979.
[src:chicago/chicago-p01] Pope Leo XIV was born in Chicago in 1955 and graduated from the Catholic Theological Union in Hyde Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has the third-largest gross metropolitan product in the United States—about $670.5 billion according to September 2017 estimates.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has also been rated as having the most balanced economy in the United States, due to its high level of diversification.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area has the third-largest science and engineering work force of any metropolitan area in the nation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago was the base of commercial operations for industrialists John Crerar, John Whitfield Bunn, Richard Teller Crane, Marshall Field, John Farwell, Julius Rosenwald, and many other commercial visionaries who laid the foundation for Midwestern and global industry.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world financial center, with the second-largest central business district in the United States, following Midtown Manhattan.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city is the seat of the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, the Bank's Seventh District.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has major financial and futures exchanges, including the Chicago Stock Exchange, the Cboe Global Markets Options Exchange, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (the "Merc"), which is owned, along with the Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT), by Chicago's CME Group.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 2017, Chicago exchanges traded 4.7 billion in derivatives.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chase Bank has its commercial and retail banking headquarters in Chicago's Chase Tower.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Academically, Chicago has been influential through the Chicago school of economics, which fielded 12 Nobel Prize winners.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city and its surrounding metropolitan area contain the third-largest labor pool in the United States with about 4.63 million workers.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Illinois is home to 66 *Fortune* 1000 companies, including those in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city of Chicago also hosts 12 *Fortune* Global 500 companies and 17 *Financial Times* 500 companies.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city claims three Dow 30 companies: aerospace giant Boeing, which moved its headquarters from Seattle to the Chicago Loop in 2001; McDonald's; and Walgreens Boots Alliance.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] For six consecutive years from 2013 through 2018, Chicago was ranked the nation's top metropolitan area for corporate relocations.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] However, three *Fortune* 500 companies left Chicago in 2022, leaving the city with 35, still second to New York City.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Manufacturing, printing, publishing, and food processing also play major roles in the city's economy.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Several medical products and services companies are based in the Chicago area, including Baxter International, Boeing, Abbott Laboratories, and the Healthcare division of General Electric.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Prominent food companies based in Chicago include the world headquarters of Conagra, Ferrara Candy Company, Kraft Heinz, McDonald's, Mondelez International, and Quaker Oats.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has been a hub of the retail sector since its early development, with Montgomery Ward, Sears, and Marshall Field's.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Today the Chicago metropolitan area is the headquarters of several retailers, including Walgreens, Sears, Ace Hardware, Claire's, ULTA Beauty, and Crate & Barrel.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Tech companies based in the area include CDW, Uber Frieght, Zebra Technologies, Motorola Solutions, Motorola along with regional offices for Google, Salesforce, LinkedIn, and more.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago was also the site of the Schwinn Bicycle Company.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago is a major world convention destination.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city's main convention center is McCormick Place.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] With its four interconnected buildings, it is the largest convention center in the nation and third-largest in the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] (behind Las Vegas and Orlando) in number of conventions hosted annually.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago's minimum wage for non-tipped employees is one of the highest in the nation and reached $15 in 2021.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city's waterfront location and nightlife attracts residents and tourists alike.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Over a third of the city population is concentrated in the lakefront neighborhoods from Rogers Park in the north to South Shore in the south.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has many upscale dining establishments as well as many ethnic restaurant districts.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Downtown is the center of Chicago's financial, cultural, governmental, and commercial institutions and the site of Grant Park and many of the city's skyscrapers.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Many of the city's financial institutions, such as the CBOT and the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago, are located within a section of downtown called "The Loop", which is an eight-block by five-block area of city streets that is encircled by elevated rail tracks.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The term "The Loop" is largely used by locals to refer to the entire downtown area as well.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The central area includes the Near North Side, the Near South Side, and the Near West Side, as well as the Loop.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] These areas contribute famous skyscrapers, abundant restaurants, shopping, museums, Soldier Field, convention facilities, parkland, and beaches.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park contains Lincoln Park Zoo and Lincoln Park Conservatory.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The River North Gallery District features the nation's largest concentration of contemporary art galleries outside of New York City.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Lake View is home to Boystown, the city's large LGBT nightlife and culture center.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Pride Parade, held the last Sunday in June, is one of the world's largest with over a million people in attendance.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] North Halsted Street is the main thoroughfare of Boystown.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The South Side neighborhood of Hyde Park is the home of former U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The neighborhood is home to the Barack Obama Presidential Center, a museum and library dedicated to his presidency.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] It also contains the University of Chicago, ranked one of the world's top ten universities, and the Museum of Science and Industry.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The 6-mile (9.7 km) long Burnham Park stretches along the waterfront of the South Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Two of the city's largest parks are also located on this side of the city: Jackson Park, bordering the waterfront, hosted the World's Columbian Exposition in 1893, and is the site of the aforementioned museum; and slightly west sits Washington Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The two parks themselves are connected by a wide strip of parkland called the Midway Plaisance, running adjacent to the University of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The South Side hosts one of the city's largest parades, the annual African American Bud Billiken Parade and Picnic, which travels through Bronzeville to Washington Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Ford Motor Company has an automobile assembly plant on the South Side in Hegewisch, and most of the facilities of the Port of Chicago are also on the South Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The West Side holds the Garfield Park Conservatory, one of the largest collections of tropical plants in any U.S. city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Prominent Latino cultural attractions found here include Humboldt Park's Institute of Puerto Rican Arts and Culture and the annual Puerto Rican People's Parade, as well as the National Museum of Mexican Art and St.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Near West Side holds the University of Illinois at Chicago and was once home to Oprah Winfrey's Harpo Studios, the site of which has been rebuilt as the global headquarters of McDonald's.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city's distinctive accent, made famous by its use in classic films like *The Blues Brothers* and television programs like the *Saturday Night Live* skit "Bill Swerski's Superfans", is an advanced form of Inland Northern American English.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] This dialect can be found in other cities bordering the Great Lakes, such as Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee, and Buffalo, New York, and most prominently features a rearrangement of certain vowel sounds, such as the short "a" sound as in "cat", which can sound more like "kyet" to outsiders.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The accent remains well associated with the city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Renowned Chicago theater companies include the Goodman Theatre in the Loop; the Steppenwolf Theatre Company and Victory Gardens Theater in Lincoln Park; and the Chicago Shakespeare Theater at Navy Pier.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Broadway In Chicago offers Broadway-style entertainment at five theaters: the Nederlander Theatre, CIBC Theatre, Cadillac Palace Theatre, Auditorium Building of Roosevelt University, and Broadway Playhouse at Water Tower Place.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Polish language productions for Chicago's large Polish speaking population can be seen at the historic Gateway Theatre in Jefferson Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Since 1968, the Joseph Jefferson Awards are given annually to acknowledge excellence in theater in the Chicago area.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago's theater community spawned modern improvisational theater, and includes the prominent groups The Second City and I.O.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Symphony Orchestra (CSO) performs at Symphony Center, and is recognized as one of the best orchestras in the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Also performing regularly at Symphony Center is the Chicago Sinfonietta, a more diverse and multicultural counterpart to the CSO.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In the summer, many outdoor concerts are given in Grant Park and Millennium Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Ravinia Festival, located 25 miles (40 km) north of Chicago, is the summer home of the CSO, and is a favorite destination for many Chicagoans.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Civic Opera House is home to the Lyric Opera of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Lithuanian Opera Company of Chicago was founded by Lithuanian Chicagoans in 1956, and presents operas in Lithuanian.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Joffrey Ballet and Chicago Festival Ballet perform in various venues, including the Harris Theater in Millennium Park.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has several other contemporary and jazz dance troupes, such as the Hubbard Street Dance Chicago and Chicago Dance Crash.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Other live-music genre which are part of the city's cultural heritage include Chicago blues, Chicago soul, jazz, and gospel.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city is the birthplace of house music (a popular form of electronic dance music) and industrial music, and is the site of an influential hip hop scene.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In the 1980s and 90s, the city was the global center for house and industrial music, two forms of music created in Chicago, as well as being popular for alternative rock, punk, and new wave.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has been a center for rave culture, since the 1980s.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A flourishing independent rock music culture brought forth Chicago indie.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various acts, such as Lollapalooza and the Pitchfork Music Festival.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Lollapalooza originated in 1991 as a touring festival, but as of 2005 its home has been Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A 2007 report on the Chicago music industry by the University of Chicago Cultural Policy Center ranked Chicago third among metropolitan U.S. areas in "size of music industry" and fourth among all U.S. cities in "number of concerts and performances".
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has a distinctive fine art tradition.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] For much of the twentieth century, it nurtured a strong style of figurative surrealism, as in the works of Ivan Albright and Ed Paschke.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 1968 and 1969, members of the Chicago Imagists, such as Roger Brown, Leon Golub, Robert Lostutter, Jim Nutt, and Barbara Rossi produced bizarre representational paintings.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Henry Darger is one of the most celebrated figures of outsider art.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 2014, Chicago attracted 50.17 million domestic leisure travelers, 11.09 million domestic business travelers and 1.308 million overseas visitors.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] These visitors contributed more than US$13.7 billion to Chicago's economy.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Upscale shopping along the Magnificent Mile and State Street, thousands of restaurants, as well as Chicago's architecture, continue to draw tourists.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city is the United States' third-largest convention destination.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A 2017 study by Walk Score ranked Chicago the sixth-most walkable of fifty largest cities in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Most conventions are held at McCormick Place, just south of Soldier Field.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Navy Pier, located just east of Streeterville, is 3,000 ft (910 m) long and houses retail stores, restaurants, museums, exhibition halls and auditoriums.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Ferris wheel first appeared at the World's Columbian Exposition, held in Chicago in 1893.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Willis Tower, formerly named Sears Tower, is a popular destination for tourists.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Among the city's museums are the Adler Planetarium & Astronomy Museum, the Field Museum of Natural History, and the Shedd Aquarium.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Museum Campus joins the southern section of Grant Park, which includes the renowned Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Buckingham Fountain anchors the downtown park along the lakefront.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The University of Chicago's Institute for the Study of Ancient Cultures, West Asia & North Africa has an extensive collection of ancient Egyptian and Near Eastern archaeological artifacts.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago lays claim to a large number of regional specialties that reflect the city's ethnic and working-class roots.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Included among these are its nationally renowned deep-dish pizza; this style is said to have originated at Pizzeria Uno.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style thin crust is also popular in the city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Certain Chicago pizza favorites include Lou Malnati's and Giordano's.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago-style hot dog, typically an all-beef hot dog, is loaded with an array of toppings that often includes pickle relish, yellow mustard, pickled sport peppers, tomato wedges, dill pickle spear and topped off with celery salt on a poppy seed bun.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Enthusiasts of the Chicago-style hot dog frown upon the use of ketchup as a garnish, but may prefer to add giardiniera.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A distinctly Chicago sandwich, the Italian beef sandwich is thinly sliced beef simmered in au jus and served on an Italian roll with sweet peppers or spicy giardiniera.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A popular modification is the Combo—an Italian beef sandwich with the addition of an Italian sausage.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Maxwell Street Polish is a grilled or deep-fried kielbasa—on a hot dog roll, topped with grilled onions, yellow mustard, and hot sport peppers.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicken Vesuvio is roasted bone-in chicken cooked in oil and garlic next to garlicky oven-roasted potato wedges and a sprinkling of green peas.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Puerto Rican-influenced jibarito is a sandwich made with flattened, fried green plantains instead of bread.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The mother-in-law is a tamale topped with chili and served on a hot dog bun.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The tradition of serving the Greek dish saganaki while aflame has its origins in Chicago's Greek community.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The appetizer, which consists of a square of fried cheese, is doused with Metaxa and flambéed table-side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago-style barbecue features hardwood smoked rib tips and hot links which were traditionally cooked in an aquarium smoker, a Chicago invention.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Annual festivals feature various Chicago signature dishes, such as Taste of Chicago and the Chicago Food Truck Festival.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] One of the world's most decorated restaurants and a recipient of three Michelin stars, Alinea is located in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Well-known chefs who have had restaurants in Chicago include: Charlie Trotter, Rick Tramonto, Grant Achatz, and Rick Bayless.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 2003, *Robb Report* named Chicago the country's "most exceptional dining destination".
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago literature finds its roots in the city's tradition of lucid, direct journalism, lending to a strong tradition of social realism.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Narrative fiction of that time, much of it in the style of "high-flown romance" and "genteel realism", needed a new approach to describe the urban social, political, and economic conditions of Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Nonetheless, Chicagoans worked hard to create a literary tradition that would stand the test of time, and create a "city of feeling" out of concrete, steel, vast lake, and open prairie.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Much notable Chicago fiction focuses on the city itself, with social criticism keeping exultation in check.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] At least three short periods in the history of Chicago have had a lasting influence on American literature.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] These include from the time of the Great Chicago Fire to about 1900, what became known as the Chicago Literary Renaissance in the 1910s and early 1920s, and the period of the Great Depression to the 1940s.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] What would become the influential *Poetry* magazine was founded in 1912 by Harriet Monroe, who was working as an art critic for the *Chicago Tribune*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The magazine discovered such poets as Gwendolyn Brooks, James Merrill, and John Ashbery.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Eliot's first professionally published poem, "The Love Song of J.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Alfred Prufrock", was first published by *Poetry*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Contributors have included Ezra Pound, William Butler Yeats, William Carlos Williams, Langston Hughes, and Carl Sandburg, among others.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The magazine was instrumental in launching the Imagist and Objectivist poetic movements.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, American poetry continued to evolve in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In the 1980s, a modern form of poetry performance began in Chicago, the poetry slam.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has two Major League Baseball (MLB) teams: the Chicago Cubs of the National League play in Wrigley Field on the North Side; and the Chicago White Sox of the American League play in Rate Field on the South Side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The two teams have faced each other in a World Series only once, in 1906.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Cubs are the oldest Major League Baseball team to have never changed their city; they have played in Chicago since 1871.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] They had the dubious honor of having the longest championship drought in American professional sports, failing to win a World Series between 1908 and 2016.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The White Sox have played on the South Side continuously since 1901.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] They have won three World Series titles (1906, 1917, 2005) and six American League pennants, including the first in 1901.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bears, one of the last two remaining charter members of the National Football League (NFL), have won nine NFL Championships, including the 1985 Super Bowl XX.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Bears play their home games at Soldier Field.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Bulls of the National Basketball Association (NBA) is one of the most recognized basketball teams in the world.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] During the 1990s, with Michael Jordan leading them, the Bulls won six NBA championships in eight seasons.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Blackhawks of the National Hockey League (NHL) began play in 1926, and are one of the "Original Six" teams of the NHL.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Blackhawks have won six Stanley Cups, including in 2010, 2013, and 2015.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Both the Bulls and the Blackhawks play at the United Center.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago Fire FC is a member of Major League Soccer (MLS) and plays at Soldier Field.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Fire have won one league title and four U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Open Cups, since their founding in 1997.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 1994, the United States hosted a successful FIFA World Cup with games played at Soldier Field.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Stars FC are a team in the National Women's Soccer League (NWSL).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] They previously played in Women's Professional Soccer (WPS), of which they were a founding member, before joining the NWSL in 2013.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] They play at SeatGeek Stadium in Bridgeview, Illinois.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Sky is a professional basketball team playing in the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] They play home games at the Wintrust Arena.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The team was founded before the 2006 WNBA season began.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon has been held each year since 1977 except for 1987, when a half marathon was run in its place.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Marathon is one of six World Marathon Majors.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Street Course in downtown Chicago had races in the Cup Series and Xfinity Series from 2023 to 2025, while the often forgotten Chicago Motor Speedway held CART and NASCAR Truck Series races.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has also entered into esports with the creation of the OpTic Chicago, a professional Call of Duty team that participates within the CDL.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] When Chicago was incorporated in 1837, it chose the motto *Urbs in Horto*, a Latin phrase which means "City in a Garden".
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Today, the Chicago Park District consists of more than 570 parks with over 8,000 acres (3,200 ha) of municipal parkland.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] There are 31 sand beaches, a plethora of museums, two world-class conservatories, and 50 nature areas.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Lincoln Park, the largest of the city's parks, covers 1,200 acres (490 ha) and has over 20 million visitors each year, making it third in the number of visitors after Central Park in New York City, and the National Mall and Memorial Parks in Washington, D.C.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] There is a historic boulevard system, a network of wide, tree-lined boulevards which connect a number of Chicago parks.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The boulevards and the parks were authorized by the Illinois legislature in 1869.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A number of Chicago neighborhoods emerged along these roadways in the 19th century.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The building of the boulevard system continued intermittently until 1942.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] It includes nineteen boulevards, eight parks, and six squares, along twenty-six miles of interconnected streets.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The *Chicago Park Boulevard System Historic District* was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2018.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] With berths for more than 6,000 boats, the Chicago Park District operates the nation's largest municipal harbor system.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Washington Park is also one of the city's biggest parks; covering nearly 400 acres (160 ha).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The park is listed on the National Register of Historic Places listings in South Side Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The government of the City of Chicago is divided into executive and legislative branches.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The mayor of Chicago is the chief executive, elected by general election for a term of four years, with no term limits.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The mayor appoints commissioners and other officials who oversee the various departments.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] As well as the mayor, Chicago's clerk and treasurer are also elected citywide.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The City Council is the legislative branch and is made up of 50 alderpersons, one elected from each ward in the city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The council takes official action through the passage of ordinances and resolutions and approves the city budget.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Police Department provides law enforcement and the Chicago Fire Department provides fire suppression and emergency medical services for the city and its residents.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Civil and criminal law cases are heard in the Cook County Circuit Court of the State of Illinois court system, or in the Northern District of Illinois, in the federal system.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In the state court, the public prosecutor is the Illinois state's attorney; in the Federal court it is the United States attorney.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] During much of the last half of the 19th century, Chicago's politics were dominated by a growing Democratic Party organization.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] During the 1880s and 1890s, Chicago had a powerful radical tradition with large and highly organized socialist, anarchist and labor organizations.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] For much of the 20th century, Chicago has been among the largest and most reliable Democratic strongholds in the United States; with Chicago's Democratic vote the state of Illinois has been "solid blue" in presidential elections since 1992.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Even before then, it was not unheard of for Republican presidential candidates to win handily in downstate Illinois, only to lose statewide due to large Democratic margins in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The citizens of Chicago have not elected a Republican mayor since 1927, when William Thompson was voted into office.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The strength of the party in Chicago is partly a consequence of Illinois state politics, where the Republicans have come to represent rural and farm concerns while the Democrats support urban issues such as Chicago's public school funding.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago contains less than 25% of the state's population, but it is split between eight of Illinois' 17 districts in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] All eight of the city's representatives are Democrats; only two Republicans have represented a significant portion of the city since 1973, for one term each: Robert P.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Hanrahan from 1973 to 1975, and Michael Patrick Flanagan from 1995 to 1997.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Machine politics persisted in Chicago after the decline of similar machines in other large U.S. cities.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] During much of that time, the city administration found opposition mainly from a liberal "independent" faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The independents finally gained control of city government in 1983 with the election of Harold Washington (in office 1983–1987).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] From 1989 until May 16, 2011, Chicago was under the leadership of its longest-serving mayor, Richard M.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Because of the dominance of the Democratic Party in Chicago, the Democratic primary vote held in the spring is generally more significant than the general elections in November for U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The aldermanic, mayoral, and other city offices are filled through nonpartisan elections with runoffs as needed.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city is home of former United States President Barack Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama; Barack Obama was formerly a state legislator representing Chicago and later a U.S. senator.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Obamas' residence is located near the University of Chicago in Kenwood on the city's south side.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago experienced major rises in violent crime in the 1920s, in the late 1960s, and in the 2020s.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago's biggest criminal justice challenges have changed little over the last 50 years, and statistically reside with homicide, armed robbery, gang violence, and aggravated battery.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has a higher murder rate than the larger cities of New York and Los Angeles.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] However, while it has a large absolute number of crimes due to its size, Chicago is not among the top-25 most violent cities in the United States.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Murder rates in Chicago vary greatly depending on the neighborhood in question.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The neighborhoods of Englewood on the South Side, and Austin on the West side, for example, have homicide rates that are ten times higher than other parts of the city.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has an estimated population of over 100,000 active gang members from nearly 60 factions.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] According to reports in 2013, "most of Chicago's violent crime comes from gangs trying to maintain control of drug-selling territories," and is specifically related to the activities of the Sinaloa Cartel, which is active in several American cities.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Violent crime rates vary significantly by area of the city, with more economically developed areas having low rates, but other sections have much higher rates of crime.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In 2013, the violent crime rate was 910 per 100,000 people; the murder rate was 10.4 per 100,000 – while high crime districts saw 38.9 murders, low crime districts saw 2.5 murders per 100,000.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago's long history of public corruption regularly draws the attention of federal law enforcement and federal prosecutors.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] From 2012 to 2019, 33 Chicago alderpersons were convicted on corruption charges, roughly one third of those elected in the time period.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A report from the Office of the Legislative Inspector General noted that over half of Chicago's elected alderpersons took illegal campaign contributions in 2013.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Most corruption cases in Chicago are prosecuted by the U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Attorney's office, as legal jurisdiction makes most offenses punishable as a federal crime.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago Public Schools (CPS) is the governing body of the school district that contains over 600 public elementary and high schools citywide, including several selective-admission magnet schools.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] There are eleven selective enrollment high schools in the Chicago Public Schools, designed to meet the needs of Chicago's most academically advanced students.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] These schools offer a rigorous curriculum with mainly honors and Advanced Placement (AP) courses.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Walter Payton College Prep High School is ranked number one in the city of Chicago and the state of Illinois.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago high school rankings are determined by the average test scores on state achievement tests.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The district, with an enrollment exceeding 400,545 students (2013–2014 20th Day Enrollment), is the third-largest in the U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] In September 2012, teachers for the Chicago Teachers Union went on strike for the first time since 1987 over pay, resources, and other issues.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] According to 2014 data, Chicago's "choice system", where students who test or apply and may attend one of approximately 130 public high schools, sorts students of different achievement levels into different schools (high performing, middle performing, and low performing schools).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has a network of Lutheran schools, and several private schools are run by other denominations and faiths, such as the Ida Crown Jewish Academy in West Ridge.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago operates Catholic schools, including Jesuit preparatory schools and others.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] A number of private schools are completely secular.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] There is also the private Chicago Academy for the Arts, a high school focused on six different artistic disciplines, and the public Chicago High School for the Arts, a high school focused on five disciplines (visual arts, theatre, musical theatre, dance, and music).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago Public Library system operates three regional libraries and 77 neighborhood branches, including the central library.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Since the 1850s, Chicago has been a world center of higher education and research with several universities.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] These institutions consistently rank among the top "National Universities" in the United States, as determined by *U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Highly regarded universities in Chicago and the surrounding area are the University of Chicago; Northwestern University; Illinois Institute of Technology; Loyola University Chicago; DePaul University; Columbia College Chicago and the University of Illinois Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] William Rainey Harper, the first president of the University of Chicago, was instrumental in the creation of the junior college concept, establishing nearby Joliet Junior College as the first in the nation in 1901.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] His legacy continues with the multiple community colleges in the Chicago proper, including the seven City Colleges of Chicago: Richard J.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Daley College, Kennedy–King College, Malcolm X College, Olive–Harvey College, Truman College, Harold Washington College, and Wilbur Wright College, in addition to the privately held MacCormac College.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The Chicago metropolitan area is a major media hub and the third-largest media market in the United States, after New York City and Los Angeles.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Each of the big five U.S. television networks, NBC, ABC, CBS, Fox and The CW, directly owns and operates a high-definition television station in Chicago (WMAQ 5, WLS 7, WBBM 2, WFLD 32 and WGN-TV 9, respectively).
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] WGN is owned by the CW through a majority stake held in the network by the Nexstar Media Group, which acquired it from its founding owner Tribune Broadcasting in 2019.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] WGN was once carried, with some programming differences, as "WGN America" on cable and satellite TV nationwide and in parts of the Caribbean.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] WGN America eventually became NewsNation in 2021.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has been the home of several prominent talk shows, including *The Oprah Winfrey Show*, *Steve Harvey Show*, *The Rosie Show*, *The Jerry Springer Show*, *The Phil Donahue Show*, *The Jenny Jones Show*, and more.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The city has one PBS member station (its second: WYCC 20, removed its affiliation with PBS in 2017): WTTW 11, producer of shows such as *Sneak Previews*, *The Frugal Gourmet*, *Lamb Chop's Play-Along* and *The McLaughlin Group*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] As of 2018, *Windy City Live* is Chicago's only daytime talk show, which is hosted by Val Warner and Ryan Chiaverini at ABC7 Studios with a live weekday audience.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Since 1999, *Judge Mathis* also films his syndicated arbitration-based reality court show at the NBC Tower.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Beginning in January 2019, *Newsy* began producing 12 of its 14 hours of live news programming per day from its new facility in Chicago.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Most of Chicago's television stations are owned and operated by the big television network companies.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Two major daily newspapers are published in Chicago: the *Chicago Tribune* and the *Chicago Sun-Times*, with the Tribune having the larger circulation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] The entertainment and cultural magazine *Time Out Chicago* and *GRAB* magazine are published in the city, as well as local music magazine *Chicago Innerview*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago is the home of satirical national news outlet, *The Onion*, and its sister pop-culture publication, *The A.V.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago has five 50,000 watt AM radio stations: the Audacy-owned WBBM and WSCR; the Tribune Broadcasting-owned WGN; the Cumulus Media-owned WLS; and the ESPN Radio-owned WMVP.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] Chicago is also home to a number of national radio shows, including *Beyond the Beltway* with Bruce DuMont on Sunday evenings.
[src:chicago/chicago-p02] WBEZ produces nationally aired programs such as PRI's *This American Life* and NPR's *Wait Wait...Don't Tell Me!*.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Chicago is a major transportation hub in the United States and North America.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] It is an important component in global distribution, as it is the third-largest inter-modal port in the world after Hong Kong and Singapore.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The city of Chicago has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] In 2015, 26.5 percent of Chicago households were without a car, and increased slightly to 27.5 percent in 2016.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Chicago averaged 1.12 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Due to Chicago's wheel tax, residents of Chicago who own a vehicle are required to purchase a Chicago City Vehicle Sticker.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] In established Residential Parking Zones, only local residents can purchase Zone-specific parking stickers for themselves and guests.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Chicago since 2009 has relinquished rights to its public street parking.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] In 2008, as Chicago struggled to close a growing budget deficit, the city agreed to a 75-year, $1.16 billion deal to lease its parking meter system to an operating company created by Morgan Stanley, called Chicago Parking Meters LLC.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The rights of the parking ticket lease end in 2081, and since 2022 have already recouped over $1.5 billion in revenue for Chicago Parking Meters LLC investors.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Eight mainline and four auxiliary interstate highways (41 (mostly in Wisconsin), 55, 57, 65 (only in Indiana), 80 (also in Indiana), 88, 90 (also in Indiana), 94 (also in Indiana), 190, 290, 294, and 355) run through Chicago and its suburbs.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] I-490 is currently under construction on the west side of O'Hare Airport.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Segments that link to the city center are named after influential politicians, with three of them named after former U.S.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Presidents (Eisenhower, Kennedy, and Reagan) and one named after two-time Democratic candidate Adlai Stevenson.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The Kennedy and Dan Ryan Expressways are the busiest state maintained routes in the entire state of Illinois.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The Regional Transportation Authority (RTA) coordinates the operation of the three service boards: CTA, Metra, and Pace.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Beginning in June 2026, the RTA will be replaced by the Northern Illinois Transit Authority (NITA).
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The Northern Indiana Commuter Transportation District (NICTD) operates the South Shore Line, which provides commuter rail service from Millennium Station to Northwest Indiana.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Since March 2026, it consists of two services: the Lakeshore Corridor to South Bend and the Monon Corridor to Munster/Dyer.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Greyhound Lines provides inter-city bus service to and from the city at the Chicago Bus Station, and Chicago is also the hub for the Midwest network of Megabus.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Amtrak long distance and inter-city rail services originate from Chicago Union Station.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Chicago is one of the largest hubs of passenger rail service in the nation.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] The services terminate in Port Huron, St.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Paul, the San Francisco Area, New York City, New Orleans, Portland, Oregon, Seattle, Miami, Milwaukee, Carbondale, Quincy, Boston, St.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Louis, Kansas City, Grand Rapids, Los Angeles, San Antonio, and Pontiac, Michigan.
[src:chicago/chicago-p03] Future service will terminate at Moline.
